## Phase 7 — Data Storage (Cloud Sync)

### How it works — detailed design

The app uses **Room** (local SQLite) as the primary data store and **Firestore** as the cloud backup. The sync is **bi-directional**: changes made on the device push to Firestore, and when a user signs in on a new device, data is pulled from Firestore.

**Firestore document structure:**
```
users/
  {userId}/
    tasks/
      {taskId} → { title, description, date, startTime, endTime, isTimeBoxed, isCompleted, ... , updatedAt, deletedAt }
    notes/
      {noteId} → { title, content, categoryId, linkedDate, ... , updatedAt, deletedAt }
    subtasks/
      {subtaskId} → { parentIdStr, title, startTime, endTime, isCompleted, updatedAt, deletedAt }
    presets/
      {presetId} → { name, scheduleJson, createdAt, updatedAt }
    gamification/
      stats → { totalXp, level, tasksCompleted, notesCreated, streakDays, lastActiveDate }
    sync_metadata/
      info → { lastSyncTimestamp }
```

**Sync flow:**

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant App as Room (Local)
    participant SM as SyncManager
    participant FS as Firestore (Cloud)
    
    Note over SM: Triggered on: app launch, task/note change, manual sync
    SM->>App: Get all items where updatedAt > lastSyncTimestamp
    SM->>FS: Get all items where updatedAt > lastSyncTimestamp
    SM->>SM: Merge using last-write-wins (compare updatedAt)
    SM->>App: Upsert merged items locally
    SM->>FS: Upsert merged items to cloud
    SM->>App: Update lastSyncTimestamp
```

**Conflict resolution — last-write-wins:**
- Every entity gets `updatedAt: Long` (epoch ms) set on every local change
- On sync, for each entity ID that exists both locally and in Firestore:
  - If local `updatedAt` > cloud `updatedAt` → push local to cloud
  - If cloud `updatedAt` > local `updatedAt` → pull cloud to local
  - If equal → no action
- Soft deletes: instead of removing rows, set `deletedAt` timestamp. During sync, a delete propagates to the other side.

**When sync happens:**
1. **On app launch** — full sync after authentication succeeds
2. **On data change** — debounced (wait 2 seconds after last change, then push)
3. **Manual** — "Force Sync" button on settings page
4. **Background** — periodic WorkManager job every 15 minutes

### 7.1 Entity changes

#### [MODIFY] All entity files (`TaskEntity`, `NoteEntity`, `SubTaskEntity`, `PresetEntity`, `GamificationEntity`)
- Add `val updatedAt: Long = System.currentTimeMillis()`
- Add `val deletedAt: Long? = null` (soft delete)
- Add `val firebaseId: String? = null` (Firestore document ID for mapping)

### 7.2 Firestore data source

#### [MODIFY] [FirestoreDataSource.kt](file:///c:/Github/app/app/src/main/java/com/example/data/network/FirestoreDataSource.kt)
- Implement per-collection CRUD:
  - `pushTasks(userId, tasks)` — batch write changed tasks
  - `pullTasks(userId, since: Long): List<TaskMap>` — query where `updatedAt > since`
  - Same pattern for notes, subtasks, presets, gamification
- Use Firestore `WriteBatch` for atomic multi-document writes
- Use `.whereGreaterThan("updatedAt", lastSyncTimestamp)` for incremental pulls

### 7.3 Sync manager

#### [NEW] `SyncManager.kt` — `com.example.data.repository`
- `suspend fun fullSync(userId: String)` — called on login and manual sync
- `suspend fun pushChanges(userId: String)` — called after local data changes (debounced)
- `suspend fun pullChanges(userId: String)` — called on app resume
- Stores `lastSyncTimestamp` in DataStore via `UserPreferencesRepository`
- Handles offline gracefully: if Firestore is unreachable, changes queue locally and sync on next connectivity

### 7.4 Background sync worker

#### [NEW] `SyncWorker.kt` — `com.example.data.repository`
- `CoroutineWorker` scheduled via `PeriodicWorkRequest` every 15 minutes
- Calls `SyncManager.fullSync()` if user is authenticated

